# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: extinct
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:extinct/adjective] An **adjective** (abbreviated **ADJ**) is a word that describes or defines a noun or noun phrase.
[src:extinct/adjective] Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.
[src:extinct/adjective] The adjective is considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns.
[src:extinct/adjective] Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including *the*, *this*, *my*, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.
[src:extinct/adjective] Depending on the language, an adjective can precede a corresponding noun on a prepositive basis or it can follow a corresponding noun on a postpositive basis.
[src:extinct/adjective] Structural, contextual, and style considerations can impinge on the pre-or post-position of an adjective in a given instance of its occurrence.
[src:extinct/adjective] Adjectives feature as a part of speech (word class) in most languages.
[src:extinct/adjective] In some languages, the words that serve the semantic function of adjectives are categorized together with some other class, such as nouns or verbs.
[src:extinct/adjective] In the phrase *a Ford car*, *Ford* is unquestionably a noun but its function is adjectival (noun adjunct, see below): to modify *car*.
[src:extinct/adjective] In some languages adjectives can function as nouns: for example, the Spanish phrase *un rojo* means 'a red [one]'.
[src:extinct/adjective] This is also possible in English, see above.
[src:extinct/adjective] As for "confusion" with verbs, rather than an adjective meaning "big", a language might have a verb that means "to be big" and could then use an attributive verb construction analogous to "big-being house" to express what in English is called a "big house".
[src:extinct/adjective] Such an analysis is possible for the grammar of Standard Chinese and Korean, for example.
[src:extinct/adjective] Different languages do not use adjectives in exactly the same situations.
[src:extinct/adjective] For example, where English uses *"*to be *hungry*" (*hungry* being an adjective), Dutch, French, and Spanish use "*honger hebben*", "*avoir faim*", and "*tener hambre*" respectively (literally "to have hunger", the words for "hunger" being nouns).
[src:extinct/adjective] Similarly, where Hebrew uses the adjective זקוק‎ (*zaqūq*, roughly "in need of" or "needing"), English uses the verb "to need".
[src:extinct/adjective] In languages that have adjectives as a word class, it is usually an open class; that is, it is relatively common for new adjectives to be formed via such processes as derivation.
[src:extinct/adjective] However, Bantu languages are well known for having only a small closed class of adjectives, and new adjectives are not easily derived.
[src:extinct/adjective] Similarly, native Japanese adjectives (*i*-adjectives) are considered a closed class (as are native verbs), although nouns (an open class) may be used in the genitive to convey some adjectival meanings, and there is also the separate open class of adjectival nouns (*na*-adjectives).
[src:extinct/adjective] Many languages (including English) distinguish between adjectives, which qualify nouns and pronouns, and adverbs, which mainly modify verbs, adjectives, or other adverbs.
[src:extinct/adjective] Not all languages make this exact distinction; many (including English) have words that can function as either.
[src:extinct/adjective] For example, in English, *fast* is an adjective in "a *fast* car" (where it qualifies the noun *car*) but an adverb in "he drove *fast*" (where it modifies the verb *drove*).
[src:extinct/adjective] A German word like *klug* ("clever(ly)") takes endings when used as an attributive adjective but not when used adverbially.
[src:extinct/adjective] Whether these are distinct parts of speech or distinct usages of the same part of speech is a question of analysis.
[src:extinct/adjective] While German linguistic terminology distinguishes *adverbiale* from *adjektivische Formen*, German refers to both as *Eigenschaftswörter* ("property words").
[src:extinct/adjective] Linguists today distinguish determiners from adjectives, considering them to be two separate parts of speech (or *lexical categories*).
[src:extinct/adjective] Determiners formerly were considered to be adjectives in some of their uses.
[src:extinct/adjective] Determiners function neither as nouns nor pronouns but instead characterize a nominal element within a particular context.
[src:extinct/adjective] They generally do this by indicating definiteness (*a* vs.
[src:extinct/adjective] An adjective acts as the head of an *adjective phrase* or *adjectival phrase* (AP).
[src:extinct/adjective] In the simplest case, an adjective phrase consists solely of the adjective; more complex adjective phrases may contain one or more adverbs modifying the adjective ("*very* strong"), or one or more complements (such as "worth *several dollars*", "full *of toys*", or "eager *to please*").
[src:extinct/adjective] In English, attributive adjective phrases that include complements typically follow the noun that they qualify ("an evildoer *devoid of redeeming qualities*").
[src:extinct/adjective] In many languages (including English) it is possible for nouns to modify other nouns.
[src:extinct/adjective] Unlike adjectives, nouns acting as modifiers (called *attributive nouns* or *noun adjuncts*) usually are not predicative; a beautiful park is beautiful, but a car park is not "car".
[src:extinct/adjective] The modifier often indicates origin ("*Virginia* reel"), purpose ("*work* clothes"), semantic patient ("*man* eater") or semantic subject ("*child* actor"); however, it may generally indicate almost any semantic relationship.
[src:extinct/adjective] It is also common for adjectives to be derived from nouns, as in *boyish*, *birdlike*, *behavioral (behavioural)*, *famous*, *manly*, *angelic*, and so on.
[src:extinct/adjective] Many languages have participle forms that can act as noun modifiers either alone or as the head of a phrase.
[src:extinct/adjective] Sometimes participles develop into functional usage as adjectives.
[src:extinct/adjective] Examples in English include *relieved* (the past participle of *relieve*), used as an adjective in passive voice constructs such as "I am so *relieved* to see you".
[src:extinct/adjective] Other examples include *spoken* (the past participle of *speak*) and *going* (the present participle of *go*), which function as attribute adjectives in such phrases as "the *spoken* word" and "the *going* rate".
[src:extinct/adjective] Other constructs that often modify nouns include prepositional phrases (as in "a rebel *without a cause*"), relative clauses (as in "the man *who wasn't there*"), and infinitive phrases (as in "a cake *to die for*").
[src:extinct/adjective] Some nouns can also take complements such as content clauses (as in "the idea *that I would do that*"), but these are not commonly considered modifiers.
[src:extinct/adjective] For more information about possible modifiers and dependents of nouns, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:extinct/adjective] In Australian Aboriginal languages, the distinction between adjectives and nouns is typically thought weak, and many of the languages only use nouns, or nouns with a limited set of adjective-deriving affixes, to modify other nouns.
[src:extinct/adjective] In languages that have a subtle adjective-noun distinction, one way to tell them apart is that a modifying adjective can come to stand in for an entire elided noun phrase, while a modifying noun cannot.
[src:extinct/adjective] For example, in Bardi, the adjective *moorrooloo* 'little' in the phrase *moorrooloo* *baawa* 'little child' can stand on its own to mean 'the little one', while the attributive noun *aamba* 'man' in the phrase *aamba baawa* 'male child' cannot stand for the whole phrase to mean 'the male one'.
[src:extinct/adjective] In other languages, like Warlpiri, nouns and adjectives are lumped together beneath the nominal umbrella because of their shared syntactic distribution as arguments of predicates.
[src:extinct/adjective] The only thing distinguishing them is that some nominals seem to semantically denote entities (typically nouns in English) and some nominals seem to denote attributes (typically adjectives in English).
[src:extinct/adjective] In many languages, attributive adjectives usually occur in a specific order.
[src:extinct/adjective] In general, the adjective order in English can be summarised as: opinion, size, age or shape, colour, origin, material, purpose.
[src:extinct/adjective] Other language authorities, like the *Cambridge Dictionary*, state that shape precedes rather than follows age.
[src:extinct/adjective] Determiners and postdeterminers—articles, numerals, and other limiters (e.g.
[src:extinct/adjective] *three* blind mice)—come before attributive adjectives in English.
[src:extinct/adjective] Although certain combinations of determiners can appear before a noun, they are far more circumscribed than adjectives in their use—typically, only a single determiner would appear before a noun or noun phrase (including any attributive adjectives).
[src:extinct/adjective] Size – adjectives denoting physical size (e.g.
[src:extinct/adjective] Shape or physical quality – adjectives describing more detailed physical attributes than overall size (e.g.
[src:extinct/adjective] Colour – adjectives denoting colour or pattern (e.g.
[src:extinct/adjective] Origin – denominal adjectives denoting source (e.g.
[src:extinct/adjective] This means that, in English, adjectives pertaining to size precede adjectives pertaining to age ("little old", not "old little"), which in turn generally precede adjectives pertaining to colour ("old white", not "white old").
[src:extinct/adjective] This order may be more rigid in some languages than others; in some, like Spanish, it may only be a default (*unmarked*) word order, with other orders being permissible.
[src:extinct/adjective] Other languages, such as Tagalog, follow their adjectival orders as rigidly as English.
[src:extinct/adjective] The normal adjectival order of English may be overridden in certain circumstances, especially when one adjective is being fronted or with ablaut reduplication.
[src:extinct/adjective] For example, the usual order of adjectives in English would result in the phrase "the bad big wolf" (opinion before size), but instead, the usual phrase is "the big bad wolf".
[src:extinct/adjective] Owing partially to borrowings from French, English has some adjectives that follow the noun as postmodifiers, called postpositive adjectives, as in *time immemorial* and *attorney general*.
[src:extinct/adjective] Adjectives may even change meaning depending on whether they precede or follow, as in *proper*: "They live in a *proper town*" (a real town, not a village) vs.
[src:extinct/adjective] "They live in the *town proper* (in the town itself, not in the suburbs).
[src:extinct/adjective] In many languages, some adjectives are *comparable* and the measure of comparison is called *degree*.
[src:extinct/adjective] For example, a person may be "polite", but another person may be "*more* polite", and a third person may be the "*most* polite" of the three.
[src:extinct/adjective] The word "more" here modifies the adjective "polite" to indicate a comparison is being made, and "most" modifies the adjective to indicate an absolute comparison (a *superlative*).
[src:extinct/adjective] Among languages that allow adjectives to be compared, different means are used to indicate comparison.
[src:extinct/adjective] Some languages do not distinguish between comparative and superlative forms.
[src:extinct/adjective] Other languages allow adjectives to be compared but do not have a special comparative form of the adjective.
[src:extinct/adjective] In such cases, as in some Australian Aboriginal languages, case-marking, such as the ablative case, may be used to indicate one entity has more of an adjectival quality than (i.e.
[src:extinct/adjective] Another way to convey comparison is by incorporating the words "more" and "most".
[src:extinct/adjective] There is no simple rule to decide which means is correct for any given adjective, however.
[src:extinct/adjective] The general tendency is for simpler adjectives and those from Anglo-Saxon to take the suffixes, while longer adjectives and those from French, Latin, or Greek do not—but sometimes the *sound* of the word is the deciding factor.
[src:extinct/adjective] Many adjectives do not naturally lend themselves to comparison.
[src:extinct/adjective] For example, some English speakers would argue that it does not make sense to say that one thing is "more ultimate" than another, or that something is "most ultimate", since the word "ultimate" is already absolute in its semantics.
[src:extinct/adjective] Such adjectives are called *non-comparable* or *absolute*.
[src:extinct/adjective] Nevertheless, native speakers will frequently play with the raised forms of adjectives of this sort.
[src:extinct/adjective] Although "pregnant" is logically non-comparable (either one is pregnant or not), one may hear a sentence like "She looks more and more pregnant each day".
[src:extinct/adjective] Comparative and superlative forms are also occasionally used for other purposes than comparison.
[src:extinct/adjective] In Italian, superlatives are frequently used to put strong emphasis on an adjective: *bellissimo* means "most beautiful", but is in fact more commonly heard in the sense "extremely beautiful".
[src:extinct/adjective] Attributive adjectives and other noun modifiers may be used either *restrictively* (helping to identify the noun's referent, hence "restricting" its reference) or *non-restrictively* (helping to describe a noun).
[src:extinct/adjective] Here "difficult" is restrictive – it tells which tasks he avoids, distinguishing these from the easy ones: "Only those tasks that are difficult".
[src:extinct/adjective] In English, restrictiveness is not marked on adjectives but is marked on relative clauses (the difference between "the man *who recognized me* was there" and "the man, *who recognized me*, was there" being one of restrictiveness).
[src:extinct/adjective] In some languages, adjectives alter their form to reflect the gender, case and number of the noun that they describe.
[src:extinct/adjective] Here, a distinction may be made between attributive and predicative usage.
[src:extinct/adjective] In English, adjectives never agree, whereas in French, they always agree.
[src:extinct/adjective] Semanticist Barbara Partee classifies adjectives semantically as intersective, subsective, or nonsubsective, with nonsubsective adjectives being plain nonsubsective or privative.
[src:extinct/extinct] Over five billion species are estimated to have died out.
[src:extinct/extinct] It is estimated that there are currently around 8.7 million species of eukaryotes globally, possibly many times more if prokaryotes are included.
[src:extinct/extinct] Notable extinct animal species include non-avian dinosaurs, saber-toothed cats, and mammoths.
[src:extinct/extinct] Through evolution, species arise through the process of speciation.
[src:extinct/extinct] Species become extinct when they are no longer able to survive in changing conditions or against superior competition.
[src:extinct/extinct] The relationship between animals and their ecological niches has been firmly established.
[src:extinct/extinct] A typical species becomes extinct within 10 million years of its first appearance, although some species, called living fossils, survive with little to no morphological change for hundreds of millions of years, though this claim has been disputed.
[src:extinct/extinct] Mass extinctions are relatively rare events; however, isolated extinctions of species and clades are quite common, and are a natural part of the evolutionary process.
[src:extinct/extinct] Only recently have extinctions begun to be recorded, and there is an ongoing mass extinction event caused by human activity.
[src:extinct/extinct] Most species that become extinct are never scientifically documented.
[src:extinct/extinct] Some scientists estimate that up to half of presently existing plant and animal species may become extinct by 2100.
[src:extinct/extinct] A 2018 report indicated that the phylogenetic diversity of 300 mammalian species erased during the human era since the Late Pleistocene would require 5 to 7 million years to recover.
[src:extinct/extinct] According to the 2019 *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* by IPBES, the biomass of wild mammals has fallen by 82%, natural ecosystems have lost about half their area and a million species are at risk of extinction—all largely as a result of human actions.
[src:extinct/extinct] Twenty-five percent of plant and animal species are threatened with extinction.
[src:extinct/extinct] In a subsequent report, IPBES listed unsustainable fishing, hunting and logging as being some of the primary drivers of the global extinction crisis.
[src:extinct/extinct] In June 2019, one million species of plants and animals were at risk of extinction.
[src:extinct/extinct] At least 571 plant species have been lost since 1750.
[src:extinct/extinct] The main cause of the extinctions is the destruction of natural habitats by human activities, such as cutting down forests and converting land into fields for farming.
[src:extinct/extinct] A dagger symbol (†) placed next to the name of a species or other taxon normally indicates its status as extinct.
[src:extinct/extinct] A species is extinct when the last existing member dies.
[src:extinct/extinct] Extinction therefore becomes a certainty when there are no surviving individuals that can reproduce and create a new generation.
[src:extinct/extinct] A species may become functionally extinct when only a handful of individuals survive, which cannot reproduce due to poor health, age, sparse distribution over a large range, a lack of individuals of both sexes (in sexually reproducing species), or other reasons.
[src:extinct/extinct] Pinpointing the extinction (or pseudoextinction) of a species requires a clear definition of that species.
[src:extinct/extinct] If it is to be declared extinct, the species in question must be uniquely distinguishable from any ancestor or daughter species, and from any other closely related species.
[src:extinct/extinct] Extinction of a species (or replacement by a daughter species) plays a key role in the punctuated equilibrium hypothesis of Stephen Jay Gould and Niles Eldredge.
[src:extinct/extinct] In ecology, *extinction* is sometimes used informally to refer to local extinction, in which a species ceases to exist in the chosen area of study, despite still existing elsewhere.
[src:extinct/extinct] Local extinctions may be made good by the reintroduction of individuals of that species taken from other locations; wolf reintroduction is an example of this.
[src:extinct/extinct] Species that are not globally extinct are termed extant.
[src:extinct/extinct] Those species that are extant, yet are threatened with extinction, are referred to as threatened or endangered species.
[src:extinct/extinct] Currently, an important aspect of extinction is human attempts to preserve critically endangered species.
[src:extinct/extinct] These are reflected by the creation of the conservation status "extinct in the wild" (EW).
[src:extinct/extinct] Species listed under this status by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) are not known to have any living specimens in the wild and are maintained only in zoos or other artificial environments.
[src:extinct/extinct] Some of these species are functionally extinct, as they are no longer part of their natural habitat and it is unlikely the species will ever be restored to the wild.
[src:extinct/extinct] When possible, modern zoological institutions try to maintain a viable population for species preservation and possible future reintroduction to the wild, through use of carefully planned breeding programs.
[src:extinct/extinct] The extinction of one species' wild population can have knock-on effects, causing further extinctions.
[src:extinct/extinct] These are also called "chains of extinction".
[src:extinct/extinct] This is especially common with extinction of keystone species.
[src:extinct/extinct] A 2018 study indicated that the sixth mass extinction started in the Late Pleistocene could take up to 5 to 7 million years to restore mammal diversity to what it was before the human era.
[src:extinct/extinct] Extinction of a parent species where daughter species or subspecies are still extant is called pseudoextinction or phyletic extinction.
[src:extinct/extinct] Effectively, the old taxon vanishes, transformed (anagenesis) into a successor, or split into more than one (cladogenesis).
[src:extinct/extinct] Pseudoextinction is difficult to demonstrate unless one has a strong chain of evidence linking a living species to members of a pre-existing species.
[src:extinct/extinct] Pseudoextinction is much easier to demonstrate for larger taxonomic groups.
[src:extinct/extinct] A Lazarus taxon or Lazarus species refers to instances where a species or taxon was thought to be extinct, but was later rediscovered.
[src:extinct/extinct] It can also refer to instances where large gaps in the fossil record of a taxon result in fossils reappearing much later, although the taxon may have ultimately become extinct at a later point.
[src:extinct/extinct] The coelacanth, a fish related to lungfish and tetrapods, is an example of a Lazarus taxon that was known only from the fossil record and was considered to have been extinct since the end of the Cretaceous Period.
[src:extinct/extinct] In 1938, however, a living specimen was found off the Chalumna River (now Tyolomnqa) on the east coast of South Africa.
[src:extinct/extinct] *Calliostoma bullatum*, a species of deepwater sea snail originally described from fossils in 1844 proved to be a Lazarus species when extant individuals were described in 2019.
[src:extinct/extinct] Attenborough's long-beaked echidna (*Zaglossus attenboroughi*) is an example of a Lazarus species from Papua New Guinea that had last been sighted in 1962 and believed to be possibly extinct, until it was recorded again in November 2023.
[src:extinct/extinct] Some species thought to be extinct have had ongoing speculation that they may still exist, and in the event of rediscovery would be considered Lazarus species.
[src:extinct/extinct] As long as species have been evolving, species have been going extinct.
[src:extinct/extinct] It is estimated that over 99.9% of all species that ever lived are extinct.
[src:extinct/extinct] The average lifespan of a species is 1–10 million years, although this varies widely between taxa.
[src:extinct/extinct] A variety of causes can contribute directly or indirectly to the extinction of a species or group of species.
[src:extinct/extinct] "Just as each species is unique", write Beverly and Stephen C.
[src:extinct/extinct] Stearns, "so is each extinction ... the causes for each are varied—some subtle and complex, others obvious and simple".
[src:extinct/extinct] Most simply, any species that cannot survive and reproduce in its environment and cannot move to a new environment where it can do so, dies out and becomes extinct.
[src:extinct/extinct] Extinction may occur a long time after the events that set it in motion, a phenomenon known as extinction debt.
[src:extinct/extinct] Assessing the relative importance of genetic factors compared to environmental ones as the causes of extinction has been compared to the debate on nature and nurture.
[src:extinct/extinct] The question of whether more extinctions in the fossil record have been caused by evolution or by competition or by predation or by disease or by catastrophe is a subject of discussion; Mark Newman, the author of *Modeling Extinction*, argues for a mathematical model that falls in all positions.
[src:extinct/extinct] By contrast, conservation biology uses the extinction vortex model to classify extinctions by cause.
[src:extinct/extinct] When concerns about human extinction have been raised, for example in Sir Martin Rees' 2003 book *Our Final Hour*, those concerns lie with the effects of climate change or technological disaster.
[src:extinct/extinct] Human-driven extinction started as humans migrated out of Africa more than 60,000 years ago.
[src:extinct/extinct] Currently, environmental groups and some governments are concerned with the extinction of species caused by humanity, and they try to prevent further extinctions through a variety of conservation programs.
[src:extinct/extinct] Humans can cause extinction of a species through overharvesting, pollution, habitat destruction, introduction of invasive species (such as new predators and food competitors), overhunting, and other influences.
[src:extinct/extinct] Explosive, unsustainable human population growth and increasing per capita consumption are essential drivers of the extinction crisis.
[src:extinct/extinct] According to the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), 784 extinctions have been recorded since the year 1500, the arbitrary date selected to define "recent" extinctions, up to the year 2004; with many more likely to have gone unnoticed.
[src:extinct/extinct] Several species have also been listed as extinct since 2004.
[src:extinct/extinct] If adaptation increasing population fitness is slower than environmental degradation plus the accumulation of slightly deleterious mutations, then a population will go extinct.
[src:extinct/extinct] Smaller populations have fewer beneficial mutations entering the population each generation, slowing adaptation.
[src:extinct/extinct] It is also easier for slightly deleterious mutations to fix in small populations; the resulting positive feedback loop between small population size and low fitness can cause mutational meltdown.
[src:extinct/extinct] Limited geographic range is the most important determinant of genus extinction at background rates but becomes increasingly irrelevant as mass extinction arises.
[src:extinct/extinct] Limited geographic range is a cause both of small population size and of greater vulnerability to local environmental catastrophes.
[src:extinct/extinct] Extinction rates can be affected not just by population size, but by any factor that affects evolvability, including balancing selection, cryptic genetic variation, phenotypic plasticity, and robustness.
[src:extinct/extinct] A diverse or deep gene pool gives a population a higher chance in the short term of surviving an adverse change in conditions.
[src:extinct/extinct] Effects that cause or reward a loss in genetic diversity can increase the chances of extinction of a species.
[src:extinct/extinct] Population bottlenecks can dramatically reduce genetic diversity by severely limiting the number of reproducing individuals and make inbreeding more frequent.
[src:extinct/extinct] Extinction sometimes results for species evolved to specific ecologies that are subjected to genetic pollution—i.e., uncontrolled hybridization, introgression and genetic swamping that lead to homogenization or out-competition from the introduced (or hybrid) species.
[src:extinct/extinct] Endemic populations can face such extinctions when new populations are imported or selectively bred by people, or when habitat modification brings previously isolated species into contact.
[src:extinct/extinct] Such extinctions are not always apparent from morphological (non-genetic) observations.
[src:extinct/extinct] Some degree of gene flow is a normal evolutionary process; nevertheless, hybridization (with or without introgression) threatens rare species' existence.
[src:extinct/extinct] The gene pool of a species or a population is the variety of genetic information in its living members.
[src:extinct/extinct] A large gene pool (extensive genetic diversity) is associated with robust populations that can survive bouts of intense selection.
[src:extinct/extinct] Meanwhile, low genetic diversity (see inbreeding and population bottlenecks) reduces the range of adaptions possible.
[src:extinct/extinct] Replacing native with alien genes narrows genetic diversity within the original population, thereby increasing the chance of extinction.
[src:extinct/extinct] Habitat degradation is currently the main anthropogenic cause of species extinctions.
[src:extinct/extinct] The main cause of habitat degradation worldwide is agriculture, with urban sprawl, logging, mining, and some fishing practices close behind.
[src:extinct/extinct] The degradation of a species' habitat may alter the fitness landscape to such an extent that the species is no longer able to survive and becomes extinct.
[src:extinct/extinct] This may occur by direct effects, such as the environment becoming toxic, or indirectly, by limiting a species' ability to compete effectively for diminished resources or against new competitor species.
[src:extinct/extinct] Habitat destruction, particularly the removal of vegetation that stabilizes soil, enhances erosion and diminishes nutrient availability in terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:extinct/extinct] This degradation can lead to a reduction in agricultural productivity.
[src:extinct/extinct] Furthermore, increased erosion contributes to poorer water quality by elevating the levels of sediment and pollutants in rivers and streams.
[src:extinct/extinct] Habitat degradation through toxicity can kill off a species very rapidly, by killing all living members through contamination or sterilizing them.
[src:extinct/extinct] It can also occur over longer periods at lower toxicity levels by affecting life span, reproductive capacity, or competitiveness.
[src:extinct/extinct] Habitat degradation can also take the form of a physical destruction of niche habitats.
[src:extinct/extinct] The widespread destruction of tropical rainforests and replacement with open pastureland is widely cited as an example of this; elimination of the dense forest eliminated the infrastructure needed by many species to survive.
[src:extinct/extinct] For example, a fern that depends on dense shade for protection from direct sunlight can no longer survive without forest to shelter it.
[src:extinct/extinct] Another example is the destruction of ocean floors by bottom trawling.
[src:extinct/extinct] Diminished resources or introduction of new competitor species also often accompany habitat degradation.
[src:extinct/extinct] Global warming has allowed some species to expand their range, bringing competition to other species that previously occupied that area.
[src:extinct/extinct] Sometimes these new competitors are predators and directly affect prey species, while at other times they may merely outcompete vulnerable species for limited resources.
[src:extinct/extinct] Vital resources including water and food can also be limited during habitat degradation, leading to extinction.
[src:extinct/extinct] Recently in geological time, humans have become an additional cause of extinction of some species, either as a new mega-predator or by transporting animals and plants from one part of the world to another.
[src:extinct/extinct] Such introductions have been occurring for thousands of years, sometimes intentionally (e.g. livestock released by sailors on islands as a future source of food) and sometimes accidentally (e.g. rats escaping from boats).
[src:extinct/extinct] In most cases, the introductions are unsuccessful, but when an invasive alien species does become established, the consequences can be catastrophic.
[src:extinct/extinct] Invasive alien species can affect native species directly by eating them, competing with them, and introducing pathogens or parasites that sicken or kill them; or indirectly by destroying or degrading their habitat.
[src:extinct/extinct] Human populations may themselves act as invasive predators.
[src:extinct/extinct] Coextinction refers to the loss of a species due to the extinction of another; for example, the extinction of parasitic insects following the loss of their hosts.
[src:extinct/extinct] Coextinction can also occur when a species loses its pollinator, or to predators in a food chain who lose their prey.
[src:extinct/extinct] "Species coextinction is a manifestation of one of the interconnectednesses of organisms in complex ecosystems ...
[src:extinct/extinct] While coextinction may not be the most important cause of species extinctions, it is certainly an insidious one." Coextinction is especially common when a keystone species goes extinct.
[src:extinct/extinct] Models suggest that coextinction is the most common form of biodiversity loss.
[src:extinct/extinct] There may be a cascade of coextinction across the trophic levels.
[src:extinct/extinct] Such effects are most severe in mutualistic and parasitic relationships.
[src:extinct/extinct] An example of coextinction is the Haast's eagle and the moa: the Haast's eagle was a predator that became extinct because its food source became extinct.
[src:extinct/extinct] The moa were several species of flightless birds that were a food source for the Haast's eagle.
[src:extinct/extinct] Extinction as a result of climate change has been confirmed by fossil studies.
[src:extinct/extinct] Particularly, the extinction of amphibians during the Carboniferous Rainforest Collapse, 305 million years ago.
[src:extinct/extinct] A 2003 review across 14 biodiversity research centers predicted that, because of climate change, 15–37% of land species would be "committed to extinction" by 2050.
[src:extinct/extinct] The ecologically rich areas that would potentially suffer the heaviest losses include the Cape Floristic Region and the Caribbean Basin.
[src:extinct/extinct] These areas might see a doubling of present carbon dioxide levels and rising temperatures that could eliminate 56,000 plant and 3,700 animal species.
[src:extinct/extinct] Climate change has also been found to be a factor in habitat loss and desertification.
[src:extinct/extinct] becoming extinct during any given time interval.
[src:extinct/extinct] It does not represent all marine species, just those that are readily fossilized.
[src:extinct/extinct] There have been at least five mass extinctions in the history of life on earth, and four in the last 350 million years in which many species have disappeared in a relatively short period of geological time.
[src:extinct/extinct] A massive eruptive event that released large quantities of tephra particles into the atmosphere is considered to be one likely cause of the "Permian–Triassic extinction event" about 250 million years ago, which is estimated to have killed 90% of species then existing.
[src:extinct/extinct] There is also evidence to suggest that this event was preceded by another mass extinction, known as Olson's Extinction.
[src:extinct/extinct] The Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event (K–Pg) occurred 66 million years ago, at the end of the Cretaceous period; it is best known for having wiped out non-avian dinosaurs, among many other species.
[src:extinct/extinct] According to a 1998 survey of 400 biologists conducted by New York's American Museum of Natural History, nearly 70% believed that the Earth is currently in the early stages of a human-caused mass extinction, known as the Holocene extinction.
[src:extinct/extinct] In that survey, the same proportion of respondents agreed with the prediction that up to 20% of all living populations could become extinct within 30 years (by 2028).
[src:extinct/extinct] A 2014 special edition of *Science* declared there is widespread consensus on the issue of human-driven mass species extinctions.
[src:extinct/extinct] Wilson estimated in 2002 that if current rates of human destruction of the biosphere continue, one-half of all plant and animal species of life on earth will be extinct in 100 years.
[src:extinct/extinct] More significantly, the current rate of global species extinctions is estimated as 100 to 1,000 times "background" rates (the average extinction rates in the evolutionary time scale of planet Earth), faster than at any other time in human history, while future rates are likely 10,000 times higher.
[src:extinct/extinct] However, some groups are going extinct much faster.
[src:extinct/extinct] Ehrlich and Stuart Pimm, among others, contend that human population growth and overconsumption are the main drivers of the modern extinction crisis.
[src:extinct/extinct] The 2020 United Nations' *Global Biodiversity Outlook* report stated that of the 20 biodiversity goals laid out by the Aichi Biodiversity Targets in 2010, only 6 were "partially achieved" by the deadline of 2020.
[src:extinct/extinct] The report warned that biodiversity will continue to decline if the status quo is not changed, in particular the "currently unsustainable patterns of production and consumption, population growth and technological developments".
[src:extinct/extinct] In a 2021 report published in the journal *Frontiers in Conservation Science*, some top scientists asserted that even if the Aichi Biodiversity Targets set for 2020 had been achieved, it would not have resulted in a significant mitigation of biodiversity loss.
[src:extinct/extinct] For much of history, the modern understanding of extinction as the end of a species was incompatible with the prevailing worldview.
[src:extinct/extinct] Prior to the 19th century, much of Western society adhered to the belief that the world was created by God and as such was complete and perfect.
[src:extinct/extinct] This concept reached its heyday in the 1700s with the peak popularity of a theological concept called the great chain of being, in which all life on earth, from the tiniest microorganism to God, is linked in a continuous chain.
[src:extinct/extinct] The extinction of a species was impossible under this model, as it would create gaps or missing links in the chain and destroy the natural order.
[src:extinct/extinct] Thomas Jefferson was a firm supporter of the great chain of being and an opponent of extinction, famously denying the extinction of the woolly mammoth on the grounds that nature never allows a race of animals to become extinct.
[src:extinct/extinct] A series of fossils were discovered in the late 17th century that appeared unlike any living species.
[src:extinct/extinct] As a result, the scientific community embarked on a voyage of creative rationalization, seeking to understand what had happened to these species within a framework that did not account for total extinction.
[src:extinct/extinct] In October 1686, Robert Hooke presented an impression of a nautilus to the Royal Society that was more than two feet in diameter, and morphologically distinct from any known living species.
[src:extinct/extinct] Hooke theorized that this was simply because the species lived in the deep ocean and no one had discovered them yet.
[src:extinct/extinct] While he contended that it was possible a species could be "lost", he thought this highly unlikely.
[src:extinct/extinct] Similarly, in 1695, Sir Thomas Molyneux published an account of enormous antlers found in Ireland that did not belong to any extant taxa in that area.
[src:extinct/extinct] Molyneux reasoned that they came from the North American moose and that the animal had once been common on the British Isles.
[src:extinct/extinct] Rather than suggest that this indicated the possibility of species going extinct, he argued that although organisms could become locally extinct, they could never be entirely lost and would continue to exist in some unknown region of the globe.
[src:extinct/extinct] The antlers were later confirmed to be from the extinct deer *Megaloceros*.
[src:extinct/extinct] Hooke and Molyneux's line of thinking was difficult to disprove.
[src:extinct/extinct] When parts of the world had not been thoroughly examined and charted, scientists could not rule out that animals found only in the fossil record were not simply "hiding" in unexplored regions of the Earth.
[src:extinct/extinct] Georges Cuvier is credited with establishing the modern conception of catastrophic extinction in a 1796 lecture to the French Institute, though he would spend most of his career trying to convince the wider scientific community of his theory.
[src:extinct/extinct] Cuvier was a well-regarded paleontologist, lauded for his ability to reconstruct the anatomy of an unknown species from a few fragments of bone.
[src:extinct/extinct] His primary evidence for extinction came from mammoth skulls found near Paris.
[src:extinct/extinct] Cuvier recognized them as distinct from any known living species of elephant, and argued that it was highly unlikely such an enormous animal would go undiscovered.
[src:extinct/extinct] In 1798, he studied a fossil from the Paris Basin that was first observed by Robert de Lamanon in 1782, first hypothesizing that it belonged to a canine but then deciding that it instead belonged to an animal that was unlike living ones.
[src:extinct/extinct] His study paved the way to his naming of the extinct mammal genus *Palaeotherium* in 1804 based on the skull and additional fossil material along with another extinct contemporary mammal genus *Anoplotherium*.
[src:extinct/extinct] In both genera, he noticed that their fossils shared some similarities with other mammals like ruminants and rhinoceroses but still had distinct differences.
[src:extinct/extinct] In 1812, Cuvier, along with Alexandre Brongniart and Geoffroy Saint-Hilaire, mapped the strata of the Paris basin.
[src:extinct/extinct] They saw alternating saltwater and freshwater deposits, as well as patterns of the appearance and disappearance of fossils throughout the record.
[src:extinct/extinct] From these patterns, Cuvier inferred historic cycles of catastrophic flooding, extinction, and repopulation of the earth with new species.
[src:extinct/extinct] Cuvier's fossil evidence showed that very different life forms had existed in the past to those that exist today, a fact that was accepted by most scientists.
[src:extinct/extinct] The primary debate focused on whether this turnover caused by extinction was gradual or abrupt in nature.
[src:extinct/extinct] Cuvier understood extinction to be the result of cataclysmic events that wipe out huge numbers of species, as opposed to the gradual decline of a species over time.
[src:extinct/extinct] In his *Essay on the Theory of the Earth* (1813), Cuvier proposed that now-extinct species had been wiped out by periodic catastrophic flooding events.
[src:extinct/extinct] His catastrophic view of the nature of extinction garnered him many opponents in the newly emerging school of uniformitarianism.
[src:extinct/extinct] Jean-Baptiste Lamarck, a gradualist and colleague of Cuvier, saw the fossils of different life forms as evidence of the mutable character of species.
[src:extinct/extinct] While Lamarck did not deny the possibility of extinction, he believed that it was exceptional and rare and that most of the change in species over time was due to gradual change.
[src:extinct/extinct] Unlike Cuvier, Lamarck was skeptical that catastrophic events of a scale large enough to cause total extinction were possible.
[src:extinct/extinct] In his geological history of the earth titled Hydrogeologie, Lamarck instead argued that the surface of the earth was shaped by gradual erosion and deposition by water, and that species changed over time in response to the changing environment.
[src:extinct/extinct] Charles Lyell, a noted geologist and founder of uniformitarianism, believed that past processes should be understood using present day processes.
[src:extinct/extinct] Like Lamarck, Lyell acknowledged that extinction could occur, noting the total extinction of the dodo and the extirpation of indigenous horses to the British Isles.
[src:extinct/extinct] He similarly argued against mass extinctions, believing that any extinction must be a gradual process.
[src:extinct/extinct] Lyell also showed that Cuvier's original interpretation of the Parisian strata was incorrect.
[src:extinct/extinct] Instead of the catastrophic floods inferred by Cuvier, Lyell demonstrated that patterns of saltwater and freshwater deposits, like those seen in the Paris basin, could be formed by a slow rise and fall of sea levels.
[src:extinct/extinct] The concept of extinction was integral to Charles Darwin's *On the Origin of Species*, with less fit lineages disappearing over time.
[src:extinct/extinct] For Darwin, extinction was a constant side effect of competition.
[src:extinct/extinct] Because of the wide reach of *On the Origin of Species*, it was widely accepted that extinction occurred gradually and evenly (a concept now referred to as background extinction).
[src:extinct/extinct] It was not until 1982, when David Raup and Jack Sepkoski published their seminal paper on mass extinctions, that Cuvier was vindicated and catastrophic extinction was accepted as an important mechanism.
[src:extinct/extinct] The current understanding of extinction is a synthesis of the cataclysmic extinction events proposed by Cuvier, and the background extinction events proposed by Lyell and Darwin.
[src:extinct/extinct] Extinction is an important research topic in the field of zoology, and biology in general, and has also become an area of concern outside the scientific community.
[src:extinct/extinct] A number of organizations, such as the Worldwide Fund for Nature, have been created with the goal of preserving species from extinction.
[src:extinct/extinct] Governments have attempted, through enacting laws, to avoid habitat destruction, agricultural over-harvesting, and pollution.
[src:extinct/extinct] While many human-caused extinctions have been accidental, humans have also engaged in the deliberate destruction of some species, such as dangerous viruses, and the total destruction of other problematic species has been suggested.
[src:extinct/extinct] Other species were deliberately driven to extinction, or nearly so, due to poaching or because they were "undesirable", or to push for other human agendas.
[src:extinct/extinct] One example was the near extinction of the American bison, which was nearly wiped out by mass hunts sanctioned by the United States government, to force the removal of Native Americans, many of whom relied on the bison for food.
[src:extinct/extinct] Biologist Bruce Walsh states three reasons for scientific interest in the preservation of species: genetic resources, ecosystem stability, and ethics; and today the scientific community "stress[es] the importance" of maintaining biodiversity.
[src:extinct/extinct] In modern times, commercial and industrial interests often have to contend with the effects of production on plant and animal life.
[src:extinct/extinct] However, some technologies with minimal, or no, proven harmful effects on *Homo sapiens* can be devastating to wildlife (for example, DDT).
[src:extinct/extinct] Governments sometimes see the loss of native species as a loss to ecotourism, and can enact laws with severe punishment against the trade in native species in an effort to prevent extinction in the wild.
[src:extinct/extinct] Nature preserves are created by governments as a means to provide continuing habitats to species crowded by human expansion.
[src:extinct/extinct] The 1992 Convention on Biological Diversity has resulted in international Biodiversity Action Plan programmes, which attempt to provide comprehensive guidelines for government biodiversity conservation.
[src:extinct/extinct] Advocacy groups, such as The Wildlands Project and the Alliance for Zero Extinctions, work to educate the public and pressure governments into action.
[src:extinct/extinct] People who live close to nature can be dependent on the survival of all the species in their environment, leaving them highly exposed to extinction risks.
[src:extinct/extinct] Anthropologist Jason Hickel speculates that the reason humanity seems largely indifferent to anthropogenic mass species extinction is that we see ourselves as separate from the natural world and the organisms within it.
[src:extinct/extinct] The poliovirus is now confined to small parts of the world due to extermination efforts.
[src:extinct/extinct] Biologist Olivia Judson has advocated the deliberate extinction of certain disease-carrying mosquito species.
[src:extinct/extinct] In an article in *The New York Times* on 25 September 2003, she advocated "specicide" of thirty mosquito species by introducing a genetic element that can insert itself into another crucial gene, to create recessive "knockout genes".
[src:extinct/extinct] She further argues that since species become extinct "all the time" the disappearance of a few more will not destroy the ecosystem: "We're not left with a wasteland every time a species vanishes.
[src:extinct/extinct] Although trials are ongoing, she writes that if they fail "we should consider the ultimate swatting".
[src:extinct/extinct] Wilson has advocated the eradication of several species of mosquito, including malaria vector *Anopheles gambiae*.
[src:extinct/extinct] Wilson stated, "I'm talking about a very small number of species that have co-evolved with us and are preying on humans, so it would certainly be acceptable to remove them.
[src:extinct/extinct] There have been many campaigns – some successful – to locally eradicate tsetse flies and their trypanosomes in areas, countries, and islands of Africa (including Príncipe).
[src:extinct/extinct] There are currently serious efforts to do away with them all across Africa, and this is generally viewed as beneficial and morally necessary, although not always.
[src:extinct/extinct] Some, such as Harvard geneticist George M.
[src:extinct/extinct] Church, believe that ongoing technological advances will let us "bring back to life" an extinct species by cloning, using DNA from the remains of that species.
[src:extinct/extinct] Proposed targets for cloning include the mammoth, the thylacine, the dodo, and the Pyrenean ibex, which has been cloned before.
[src:extinct/extinct] For this to succeed, enough individuals would have to be cloned, from the DNA of different individuals (in the case of sexually reproducing organisms) to create a viable population.
[src:extinct/extinct] Though bioethical and philosophical objections have been raised, the cloning of extinct creatures seems theoretically possible.
[src:extinct/extinct] In 2003, scientists tried to clone the extinct Pyrenean ibex (*C. p. pyrenaica*).
[src:extinct/extinct] This attempt failed: of the 285 embryos reconstructed, 54 were transferred to 12 Spanish ibexes and ibex–domestic goat hybrids, but only two survived the initial two months of gestation before they, too, died.
[src:extinct/extinct] A second attempt was made to clone the Pyrenean ibex: one clone was born alive, but died seven minutes later, due to physical defects in the lungs.
[src:extinct/noun] In grammar, a **noun** is a word that represents a concrete or abstract thing, like living creatures, places, actions, events, qualities, states of existence, and ideas.
[src:extinct/noun] To summarize this, nouns signify an object or idea.
[src:extinct/noun] A noun may serve as an object or subject within a phrase, clause, or sentence.
[src:extinct/noun] In linguistics, nouns constitute a lexical category (part of speech) defined according to how its members combine with members of other lexical categories.
[src:extinct/noun] The syntactic occurrence of nouns differs among languages.
[src:extinct/noun] In English, prototypical nouns are common nouns or proper nouns that can occur with determiners, articles and attributive adjectives, and can function as the head of a noun phrase.
[src:extinct/noun] According to traditional and popular classification, pronouns are distinct from nouns, but in much modern theory they are considered a subclass of nouns.
[src:extinct/noun] Every language has various linguistic and grammatical distinctions between nouns and verbs.
[src:extinct/noun] Word classes (parts of speech) were described by Sanskrit grammarians from at least the 5th century BC.
[src:extinct/noun] In Yāska's *Nirukta*, the noun (*nāma*) is one of the four main categories of words defined.
[src:extinct/noun] The Ancient Greek equivalent was *ónoma* (ὄνομα), referred to by Plato in the *Cratylus*, and later listed as one of the eight parts of speech in *The Art of Grammar*, attributed to Dionysius Thrax (2nd century BC).
[src:extinct/noun] The term used in Latin grammar was *nōmen*.
[src:extinct/noun] All of these terms for "noun" were also words meaning "name".
[src:extinct/noun] The English word *noun* is derived from the Latin term, through the Anglo-Norman *nom* (other forms include *nomme*, and *noun* itself).
[src:extinct/noun] The word classes were defined partly by the grammatical forms that they take.
[src:extinct/noun] In Sanskrit, Greek, and Latin, for example, nouns are categorized by gender and inflected for case and number.
[src:extinct/noun] Because adjectives share these three grammatical categories, adjectives typically were placed in the same class as nouns.
[src:extinct/noun] Similarly, the Latin term *nōmen* includes both nouns (substantives) and adjectives, as originally did the English word *noun*, the two types being distinguished as *nouns substantive* and *nouns adjective* (or *substantive nouns* and *adjective nouns*, or simply *substantives* and *adjectives*).
[src:extinct/noun] Many European languages use a cognate of the word *substantive* as the basic term for *noun* (for example, Spanish *sustantivo*, "noun").
[src:extinct/noun] Nouns in the dictionaries of such languages are demarked by the abbreviation *s.* or *sb.* instead of *n.*, which may be used for proper nouns or neuter nouns instead.
[src:extinct/noun] In English, some modern authors use the word *substantive* to refer to a class that includes both nouns (single words) and noun phrases (multiword units that are sometimes called *noun equivalents*).
[src:extinct/noun] It can also be used as a counterpart to *attributive* when distinguishing between a noun being used as the head (main word) of a noun phrase and a noun being used as a noun adjunct.
[src:extinct/noun] For example, the noun *knee* can be said to be used substantively in *my knee hurts*, but attributively in *the patient needed knee replacement*.
[src:extinct/noun] A noun can co-occur with an article or an attributive adjective.
[src:extinct/noun] In the following, an asterisk (*) in front of an example means that this example is ungrammatical.
[src:extinct/noun] Nouns have sometimes been characterized in terms of the grammatical categories by which they may be varied (for example gender, case, and number).
[src:extinct/noun] Such definitions tend to be language-specific, since different languages may apply different categories.
[src:extinct/noun] Nouns are frequently defined, particularly in informal contexts, in terms of their semantic properties (their meanings).
[src:extinct/noun] Nouns are described as words that refer to a *person*, *place*, *thing*, *event*, *substance*, *quality*, *quantity*, etc., but this manner of definition has been criticized as uninformative.
[src:extinct/noun] Several English nouns lack an intrinsic referent of their own: *behalf* (as in *on behalf of*), *dint* (*by dint of*), and *sake* (*for the sake of*).
[src:extinct/noun] Moreover, other parts of speech may have reference-like properties: the verbs *to rain* or *to mother*, or adjectives like *red*; and there is little difference between the adverb *gleefully* and the prepositional phrase *with glee*.
[src:extinct/noun] A functional approach defines a noun as a word that can be the head of a nominal phrase, i.e., a phrase with referential function, without needing to go through morphological transformation.
[src:extinct/noun] Nouns can have a number of different properties and are often sub-categorized based on various of these criteria, depending on their occurrence in a language.
[src:extinct/noun] Nouns may be classified according to morphological properties such as which prefixes or suffixes they take, and also their relations in syntax – how they combine with other words and expressions of various types.
[src:extinct/noun] Many such classifications are language-specific, given the obvious differences in syntax and morphology.
[src:extinct/noun] In English for example, it might be noted that nouns are words that can co-occur with definite articles (as stated at the start of this article), but this could not apply in Russian, which has no definite articles.
[src:extinct/noun] In some languages common and proper nouns have grammatical gender, typically masculine, feminine, and neuter.
[src:extinct/noun] The gender of a noun (as well as its number and case, where applicable) will often require agreement in words that modify or are used along with it.
[src:extinct/noun] In French for example, the singular form of the definite article is *le* for masculine nouns and *la* for feminine; adjectives and certain verb forms also change (sometimes with the simple addition of *-e* for feminine).
[src:extinct/noun] Grammatical gender often correlates with the form of the noun and the inflection pattern it follows; for example, in both Italian and Romanian most nouns ending in *-a* are feminine.
[src:extinct/noun] Gender can also correlate with the sex or social gender of the noun's referent, particularly in the case of nouns denoting people (and sometimes animals), though with exceptions (the feminine French noun *personne* can refer to a male or a female person).
[src:extinct/noun] In Modern English, even common nouns like *hen* and *princess* and proper nouns like *Alicia* do not have grammatical gender (their femininity has no relevance in syntax), though they denote persons or animals of a specific sex.
[src:extinct/noun] The gender of a pronoun must be appropriate for the item referred to: "The *girl* said the *ring* was from *her* new *boyfriend*, but *he* denied *it* was from *him*" (three nouns; and three gendered pronouns: or four, if this *her* is counted as a possessive pronoun).
[src:extinct/noun] Many nouns have both countable and uncountable uses; for example, *soda* is countable in "give me three sodas", but uncountable in "he likes soda".
[src:extinct/noun] Some nouns have both concrete and abstract meanings: *art* usually refers to something abstract ("Art is important in human culture"), but it can also refer to a concrete item ("I put my daughter's art up on the fridge").
[src:extinct/noun] A noun might have a literal (concrete) and also a figurative (abstract) meaning: "a brass *key*" and "the *key* to success"; "a *block* in the pipe" and "a mental *block*".
[src:extinct/noun] Similarly, some abstract nouns have developed etymologically by figurative extension from literal roots (*drawback*, *fraction*, *holdout*, *uptake*).
[src:extinct/noun] Many abstract nouns in English are formed by adding a suffix (*-ness*, *-ity*, *-ion*) to adjectives or verbs (*happiness* and *serenity* from the adjectives *happy* and *serene*; *circulation* from the verb *circulate*).
[src:extinct/noun] Illustrating the wide range of possible classifying principles for nouns, the Awa language of Papua New Guinea regiments nouns according to how *ownership* is assigned: as alienable possession or inalienable possession.
[src:extinct/noun] An alienably possessed item (a tree, for example) can exist even without a possessor.
[src:extinct/noun] But inalienably possessed items are necessarily associated with their possessor and are referred to differently, for example with nouns that function as kin terms (meaning "father", etc.), body-part nouns (meaning "shadow", "hair", etc.), or part–whole nouns (meaning "top", "bottom", etc.).
[src:extinct/noun] A noun phrase (or **NP**) is a phrase usually headed by a common noun, a proper noun, or a pronoun.
[src:extinct/noun] The head may be the only constituent, or it may be modified by determiners and adjectives.
[src:extinct/noun] For example, "The dog sat near Ms Curtis and wagged its tail" contains three NPs: *the dog* (subject of the verbs *sat* and *wagged*); *Ms Curtis* (complement of the preposition *near*); and *its tail* (object of *wagged*).
[src:extinct/noun] "You became their teacher" contains two NPs: *you* (subject of *became*); and *their teacher*.
[src:extinct/noun] For example, in the sentence "Gareth thought she was weird", the word *she* is a pronoun that refers to a person just as the noun *Gareth* does.
[src:extinct/noun] The word *one* can replace parts of noun phrases, and it sometimes stands in for a noun.
[src:extinct/noun] But *one* can also stand in for larger parts of a noun phrase.
[src:extinct/noun] For example, in the following example, *one* can stand in for *new car*.
[src:extinct/noun] Nominalization is a process whereby a word that belongs to another part of speech comes to be used as a noun.
[src:extinct/noun] This can be a way to create new nouns, or to use other words in ways that resemble nouns.
[src:extinct/noun] In French and Spanish, for example, adjectives frequently act as nouns referring to people who have the characteristics denoted by the adjective.
[src:extinct/noun] is a worldwide association of political parties.
